{"product_id": "368500", "page": 237, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-20", "text": "Well, as i expected, ubisoft learned with errors from the past and made a amazing game of AC franchise. few first hours playing and i saw a different game mode, skills, graphics, and few bugs. with the time, soon will disappear. dont say you didnt see any bug (like kill someone in stair and it stay inside of it or something like that) but if u didnt see you will. in overall, i highly recommend this game to everyone who enjoy the AC franchise and those who are new in AC world. easy tutorials for everyone and many explanations about AC history from anothers versions in the game. First in franchise where you can play with both characters, with different skills and own personallities. About compatibilty? using a quad-core from AMD with 8 GB and just a GTX 750 i could run the game in high graphics no problems. no freezing no lags, insteald of unity i had to run in medium sometimes in certains places. this one is perfect! gratz Ubi DEVS!", "hours": 337.8, "user_id": "76561198024154051", "username": "Mr. Tony", "products": 855, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "368500", "page": 238, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-20", "text": "This is probably one of my favorite games, with a really well done redesigned parkour system along with the amazing look and feel of the game gives it to the aspect of real life london.\nThe game starts out simple, but as you progress finding more and more about how the game works, it pushes you to thrive for more, this being the first assassin's creed that has two players that you can play as, and the first to offer the Grappling Hook.\nI deffinantly reccomend this game for being overall amazing.", "hours": 36.0, "username": "Ashleyz", "products": 454, "found_funny": 7, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "368500", "page": 238, "page_order": 1, "recommended": false, "date": "2015-11-20", "text": "Frankly, I'd like to recommend this game on a lot of levels, but one thing in particular utterly ruins the entire experience. They introduced leveling into the game. While that isn't so bad in and of itself - they made enemies that are higher level than you practically invincible badasses that'll take a hundred or more hits to kill and will also kill you in about two hits. Oh, and to make it better the levels of enemies are just randomly distributed around the city. So.. you're walking along, and totally own a group of random level 2 thugs. Walk a block over, and suddenly you're fighting the exact same thugs.. except now they're level 9 and will utterly own you without question and without the player having any chance at all. Exactly what AC games needed - an MMO leveling scheme.", "hours": 54.2, "user_id": "76561198042238818", "username": "Enorats", "products": 165, "found_funny": 12, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "368500", "page": 238, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-20", "text": "If you're using NVidia be sure to turn off MFAA in the NVidia Control Panel if you use it AND be on Driver Version 359.00! Without doing those two things you may run into issues that myself and others have ran into which range from buildings not appearing, graphical glitches everywhere, some textures looking like it's straight up Missingno from Pokemon. However with the drivers + no MFAA the game runs flawlessly!\nI guess since this is a review I should also add in my general early thoughts (2 hours in). The game itself feels like a step forward in terms of art design and the way it handles side quests. Opening up a map doesn't seem overwhelming anymore. You just have 5 or 6 clear objectives in every section of the map. It's not 1000+ little collectibles marked all over. The pacing is on point. The story is also quite good so far, I especially love the skill tree added in. Gameplay wise it seems to be a step back. Unity went for a more open ended mission structure (Syndicate could still go this way considering how early into the game I'm in) where you were given a target and a general location and all you had to do was figure out a way to kill the target. This one seems to lead you down a direct path to your targets leaving little creativity to how you dispose of targets (So AC1-4 style). It also feels like the combat is a step back. It's a counter fest again. So if you're down with the old gameplay style for another entry then it's fine. However, if you really enjoyed Unity's approach to mission structure and combat then you may feel a bit disappointed.", "hours": 17.5, "username": "Shinsuke Nakamura", "products": 1822, "found_funny": 4, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "368500", "page": 238, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2015-11-20", "text": "Playing Assassin's Creed Unity felt like the receiving of news that my family got killed by ISIS, and I had cancer.\nPlaying Assassin's Creed Syndicate feels like the receiving of news that my family killed ISIS, and they found a cure for my cancer.\n10/10 would assassinate again.", "hours": 22.8, "username": "Shern", "products": 134, "found_funny": 609, "early_access": false}
